STREP. GROUP B - SINGAPORE: SEROTYPE III, ST283, INVASIVE, FOODBORNE, RAW FISH
******************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 18 Jul 2018
From: Timothy Barkham <Timothy_Barkham@ttsh.com.sg> [edited]


re: ProMED-mail. Strep. Group B - Singapore: serotype III, ST283, invasive, foodborne, fish, 2015 20171116.5448535
-----------------------------------------------------------------

Subject: _Streptococcus agalactiae_ [Group B streptococcus] ST283, which caused a foodborne outbreak of invasive sepsis in Singapore in 2015, is widespread in humans and aquaculture in South East Asia.

Background: In 2015, Singapore had the 1st reported foodborne outbreak caused by the group B streptococcus (GBS) _Streptococcus agalactiae_. It was sequence type (ST) 283, acquired from fish, and, remarkably, affected adults without co-morbidities. Previously, ST283 had only been reported from humans in Hong Kong and one fish in Thailand.

Results of a literature review and a survey of ST238 amongst opportunistic GBS collections show that GBS ST283 accounted for 29/38 (76 per cent) invasive GBS in Lao PDR (2000-2017), 102/139 (73 per cent) in Thailand (2007-2015), 4/13 (31 per cent) in Vietnam (2015-2017), and 21/331 (6 per cent) and 146/408 (36 per cent) in Singapore (2001-2010 and 2011-2015 respectively). Only 4 cases of ST283 were reported outside Asia (2002-2017). ST283 and its variants were found in 7 fish species in Singapore markets (2015), a diseased frog in China (2014), and 68/68 (100 per cent) diseased tilapia from 14 sites in Malaysia (2007-2008 and 2018) and Vietnam (2016). Genomic analysis showed that ST283 is monophyletic and predicted it emerged in 1984, coinciding with the regional expansion of aquaculture.

Our interpretation is that ST283 is causing invasive sepsis in adult humans, and disease in farmed aquatic animals, in parts of SE Asia. Transmission routes have not been studied but the foodborne route, via consumption of raw fish, as in the Singapore outbreak, is suspected. ST283 poses a potential hazard to food security and public health in countries expanding aquaculture.

--
communicated, on behalf of numerous collaborators, by:
Dr Timothy Barkham, MBBS, MSc, FRCPath
Adjunct Associate Professor
