[ProMED-mail thanks Dr Barkham and colleagues for their submission.

Prior ProMED-mail posts (Strep. Group B - Singapore: serotype III, ST283, invasive, foodborne, fish, 2015 20171116.5448535, Strep. Group B - Singapore: foodborne susp. RFI 20150715.3513331 and Strep. Group B - Singapore (02): fish susp, RFI 20150814.3577512) reported an outbreak of invasive infections due to group B Streptococcus (GBS, also called _Streptococcus agalactiae_) serotype III sequence type (ST) 283 that sickened 238 people in Singapore in 2015. This outbreak was linked to consumption of GBS-contaminated raw fish in "yusheng", a popular dish at hawker centers (food courts), where raw fish is marinated in sesame oil and garnished with red chili and ginger. The dish typically is made from 2 freshwater fish species, Asian bighead carp and snakehead.

GBS are Gram positive cocci that produce beta-hemolysis when cultured on sheep blood agar. They are classified into several serotypes based on the antigenic specificity of their capsular polysaccharide. GBS colonize the vagina and gastrointestinal tract in healthy women, with carriage rates ranging from 15-45 per cent and can cause chorioamnionitis, post-partum endometritis, and sepsis in pregnant women and pneumonia, sepsis, and meningitis in newborns following vaginal delivery in mothers with vaginal GBS colonization at the time of delivery.

GBS have been found to colonize the urethra in both men and women and can also colonize the gastrointestinal tract and upper respiratory tract; they are increasingly recognized as an invasive pathogen in diabetics and the elderly, causing sepsis, pneumonia, skin and soft-tissue infection (such as, decubitus ulcers and diabetic foot infections), urinary tract infections, endocarditis, septic arthritis, osteomyelitis, meningitis, peritonitis, and endophthalmitis (http://cid.oxfordjournals.org/content/41/6/839.long).

GBS are also found in other animals including fish, cattle, horses, dogs, rabbits, guinea pigs, and mice. The strains that cause disease in humans, however, were said to be usually biochemically, metabolically or serologically different from strains that cause disease in other animals (http://www.cfsph.iastate.edu/Factsheets/pdfs/streptococcosis.pdf). However, GBS MLST ST-283, serotype III-4 with similar genotypes has been detected both in fish and in adult humans with invasive GBS diseases in Southeast Asia, which suggested that there may be an epidemiological connection between the 2 host species, as previously described for a closely related streptococcal species, _Streptococcus iniae_ (http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-2180/13/41). This epidemiologic connection has now been established in the Singapore outbreak (1-4).

1. Rajendram P, Mar Kyaw W, Leo YS, et al. Group B streptococcus sequence type 283 disease linked to consumption of raw fish, Singapore. Emerg Infect Dis. 2016; 22(11): 1974-1977. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5088009/.
2. Tan S, Lin Y, Foo K, et al. Group B streptococcus serotype III sequence type 283 bacteremia associated with consumption of raw fish, Singapore. Emerg Infect Dis. 2016; 22(11): 1970-1973. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5088028/.
3. Chau ML, Chen SL, Yap M, et al. Group B streptococcus infections caused by improper sourcing and handling of fish for raw consumption, Singapore, 2015-2016. Emerg Infect Dis. 2017 Dec;23(12). Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5708258/.
4. Kalimuddin S, Chen SL, Lim CTK, et al. Singapore Group B Streptococcus Consortium. 2015 epidemic of severe _Streptococcus agalactiae_ sequence type 283 infections in Singapore associated with the consumption of raw freshwater fish: a detailed analysis of clinical, epidemiological, and bacterial sequencing data. Clin Infect Dis. 2017;64(suppl_2):S145-S152. https://academic.oup.com/cid/article/64/suppl_2/S145/3782664.
- Mod.ML

